				<mj-text css-class="article">
					<h2>Coming soon in Backlight 6.0</h2>
          <p>The 6.0 release will focus almost entirely on Backlight's headlining, new blogging feature, made manifest in the new Kookaburra Blog module.</p>
          <p>Before this point, for Backlight users wanting to blog, we have recommended pairing Backlight with a WordPress deployment. No more! And I have got to say, now is a great time to not be using WordPress; more on that below.</p>
          <p>Blogging in Backlight will feel very familiar to anyone already using <a href="https://youtu.be/kj5RqHwCk08" target="_blank">Kookaburra's essay features</a>. Everything can be done in an essay, can also be done in a blog post. The difference is simply a matter of organization: essays exist in manually arranged collections, and can be mixed into sets with albums; blogs present in a chronological feed. Essays are fantastic for creating zines of evergreen content, while blogs excel for posting news and updates, logging events, making announcements, journaling, photo blogging, etc.</p>
          <p>Content will also be interchangeable between the two, meaning that you can evergreen a blog post by copy-and-pasting its content into an essay!</p>
          <p>Kookaburra Blog is a new core module in Backlight 6, and will not be sold separately as an add-on.</p>
          <p>We will delve into organizational features for blogs at time of release, but I can also tell you right now that you will be able to run multiple individual blog feeds should you like to do so. For example, you might have a daily photo blog, and a separate feed for events, workshops, or studio updates.</p>
          <p>Additionally, Backlight 6 will pack in minor updates and improvements as usual, all of which we will detail later in the 6.0 release notes.</p>
				</mj-text>        
			</mj-column>
		</mj-section>

		<mj-section>
