				<mj-image alt="" src="" />
				<mj-text css-class="article">
					<h2>WordPress is a mess right now ...</h2>
					<p>WordPress in 2024 is a bad place to be. With this in mind, we are very exciting to finally be supporting blogging in Backlight 6.</p>
          <p>In late February, 404 Media reported that <a href="https://www.404media.co/tumblr-and-wordpress-to-sell-users-data-to-train-ai-tools/" target="_blank">Tumblr and WordPress would soon be selling users' data to AI companies</a>. A few days later, they reported that <a href="https://www.404media.co/wordpress-firehose-allows-ai-companies-to-buy-access-to-a-million-posts-a-day/" target="_blank">A WordPress "Firehose" Allows AI Companies to Buy Access to a Million Posts a Day</a>, not only from sites hosted on WordPress.com, but also from personal WordPress sites using Automattic's popular JetPack plugin.</p>
          <p>The simple truth is that Automattic has never respected the privacy of WordPress users, and has been banking on users' data for years upon years. That they would be selling said data to AI companies in 2024 should come as no surprise.</p>
          <p>In early October, more shit hit the fan when WordPress.org users were forced to disavow any affiliation, financial or otherwise, with the third-party host WP Engine before registering a new account, or logging in to their existing account. Once again, 404 Media was on the beat, writing <a href="https://www.404media.co/wordpress-checkbox-login-wp-engine/" target="_blank">The Community Is In Chaos: WordPress.org Now Requires You Denounce Affiliation With WP Engine To Log In</a>. And while Automattic and WP Engine engage in slings and arrows, 404 Media continued to report that <a href="https://www.404media.co/automattic-buyout-offer-wordpress-matt-mullenweg/" target="_blank">Employees Describe an Environment of Paranoia and Fear Inside Automattic Over WordPress Chaos</a>, amid layoffs, terminations, and departures of employees from Automattic. Amongst those who remain with the company, morale is said to be at an all-time low.</p>
          <p>While Automattic and WordPress are imploding, they've dragged their garbage into the public square and exposed their users to it as well.</p>
          <p>Finally, and this isn't a new issue, but is nonetheless worth calling out, WordPress paints a target on your back for hackers. A large percentage of websites are powered by WordPress, and this pervasiveness makes it a popular target for misdeeds. And because of its modular ecosystem, plugins and extensions very often create vulnerabilities for hackers to exploit! A legitimate way to safeguard your domain is to just not use it.</p>          
          <p>And so, we are very exciting to be introducing native blogging to Backlight in our upcoming 6.0 release.</p>
          <p>This also settles the question, will there or will there not be an eventual Kookaburra WordPress theme, with a resounding NO. But rest assured, the Pangolin WP Theme add-on will remain as is for as long as we continue to support the Pangolin modules.</p>
				</mj-text>        
			</mj-column>
